 New York Harbor maritime community heroically delivered stranded commuters, residents, and visitors out of harm's way. Even before the US Coast Guard called for "all available boats," tugs, ferries, dinner boats, and other vessels had sped to the rescue from points all across New York Harbor. In less than nine hours, captains and crews transported nearly half a million people from Manhattan.Anchored in eyewitness accounts and written by a mariner who served at Ground Zero, Saved at the Seawall weaves together the personal stories of people rescued that day with those of the mariners who saved them. DuLong describes the inner workings of New York Harbor and reveals the collaborative power of its close-knit community. Her chronicle of those crucial hours, when hundreds of thousands of lives were at risk, highlights how resourcefulness and basic human goodness triumphed over turmoil on one of America's darkest days.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEmergency managementzNew York (State)zNew York. 0aEvacuation of civilianszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aRescueszNew York (State)zNew York. 0aSeptember 11 Terrorist Attacks, 2001. 4aNew York History. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Middle Atlantic (DC, DE, MD, NJ, NY, PA).2bisacsh  aboat lift, Maritime evacuation, coastguard and 9/11, waterborne rescue, Dunkirk, working harbor, tugboatds and 9/11,.1 aDuLong, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZuckoff, Mitchell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZuckoff, Mitchell.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501759130zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.c